Compiled and installed ddccontrol 0.4.2 (and
ddccontrol-db-20061014) using default options (./configure, no
args).  I get the following:

    # LANG=3D LC_ALL=3D ddccontrol -p -c -d
    ddccontrol version 0.4.2
    Copyright 2004-2005 Oleg I. Vdovikin (oleg@...13...)
    Copyright 2004-2006 Nicolas Boichat (nicolas@...3...)
    This program comes with ABSOLUTELY NO WARRANTY.
    You may redistribute copies of this program under the terms of the
GNU General Public License.

    Probing for available monitors....
    Detected monitors :
    No monitor supporting DDC/CI available.
    If your graphics card need it, please check all the required
kernel modules are loaded (i2c-dev, and your framebuffer driver).

The machine is a Fujitsu Siemens ScaleOP with an ATI Radeon
graphics controller.  Before I zapped Windows on it, I noted
the configuration Windows thought it had for the hardware:
According to Windows, it was an ATI Radeon X1700 FSC.  If I look
at what Mandriva says:

    Identification
    Vendor: ATI Technologies Inc
    Description: Unknown
    Media class: VGA compatible controller

    Connection
    Bus: PCI
    Bus PCI #: 1
    PCI device #: 0
    PCI function #: 0
    Vendor ID: 0x1002
    Device ID: 0x71c1
    Sub vendor ID: 0x174b
    Sub device ID: 0x0880

    Misc
    Module: unknown

(Naively, there are a few too many "unknown" there.)

The monitor is an LG L1900E.  When I enter the Mandrake Monitor
configuration menu, it shows "Plug'n Play (L1900E)" highlighted;
presumably, this means that the monitor has been correctly
identified.

I tried adding the modules i2c-dev and radeonfb (using modprobe)
to no avail.  (If I understand the documentation correctly, they
shouldn't be necessary if I have an ATI controller.)

I *suspect* that the problem is simply some missing or
unrecognized configuration data---both the basic system and the
monitor are new, and possibly the model identifiers aren't being
recognized at some level.  But I'm not too familiar with this.

FWIW: I also tried "ddccontrol -p -v -v", just to see what
additional information might be available.  It seems to be
finding PCI devices (pci:01:00.0-0 through pci:01:00.0-3); for
each, it generates the following messages:
Device: pci:01:00.0-0
    =3D=3D>Received!
    =3D=3D>Opening...
    =3D=3D>01:00.0-0
    =3D=3D>01:00.0 vendor=3D1002 device=3D71c1 class=3D0300 irq=3D5 base0=
=3Dd0000000
size0=3D10000000
    =3D=3D>Opened (status=3D0)...
    =3D=3D>Received!
    =3D=3D>Data, mquery->flags =3D 0
    Error while reading write message answer: Bad message
    Reading EDID 0x50 failed.
    ddcci_open returned -2

